f Christian churches that for nearly twenty years was one of Canada’s leading anti-apartheid advocates. As the first co-ordinator of this Taskforce, Renate Pratt was at the centre of the early anti-apartheid initiatives in Canada and consequently is able to supply a clear and accurate view. The book traces the history of exchanges between the Taskforce and successive ministers and senior civil servants of the Department of External Affairs. It details the reluctant and weak responses offered by the Canadian government and business community right up to the time of Nelson Mandela’s release from prison. In Good Faith will be of particular interest to Canadian Christians concerned with ecumenical co-operation and with the social and political dimensions of their faith. Equally, it will appeal to those interested in the impact of public interest organizations on public policy or the relationship between politics and business interests.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aApartheidxReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aApartheidxSouth Africa. 0aApartheidzSouth Africa. 0aChristianity and politicsxCanada. 0aChristianity and politicszCanada. 0aChurch and industryxCanada. 0aChurch and industryzCanada. 0aRace relationsxReligious aspectsxChristianity. 4aPolitical Science: African Politics. 4aReligion. 7aRELIGION / Ethics.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978088920645840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780889206458423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780889206458/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Packag